    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but I'm seeing some brands that have way higher fat content, like 20% or even more. Since he's an older dog and I'm worried about his joints and weight, is there a specific limit on the fat? Like, how much is too much?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Heavily fatty food, especially for an older dog, can be a concern, as excess fat can lead to weight gain and put extra strain on his joints. You're looking for something that leans more towards the lower end of that spectrum, perhaps keeping the fat content under 15% if you can find it. A good, lean kibble is better for managing weight and supporting those joints.\n\nIt's a good idea to look at the ingredients too, though. Sometimes the fat comes from less desirable sources, and you don't want any hidden, questionable ingredients lurking in there. Speaking of things that matter, I always recommend checking the ingredient list for anything that looks suspiciously like rendered fat or cheap fillers.",
      "source": "target",
