    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, I definitely want to avoid fillers. I noticed some brands list \"animal fat\" but don't specify what kind. Besides the fat/protein ratio, are there any other specific micronutrients or supplements that would help an aging Lab's joint health? Like glucosamine or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Glucosamine and chondroitin are definitely worth looking for, as they are excellent for supporting joint health in older dogs. You should look for a food that explicitly lists these as ingredients, or perhaps a brand that offers a specific joint support formula. You could also look into omega-3 fatty acids, specifically EPA and DHA, as those are fantastic for reducing inflammation, which is a big help for aging joints.\n\nIf you're worried about fillers, you might also want to check for high-quality sources of joint support ingredients. Sometimes, a good quality kibble will have a balanced profile, but if you're feeling particularly cautious, you could even consider a supplement mixed into his food, just to be safe.",
      "source": "target",
